=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">This may have been inevitable, given the h=
eavy pall of
negativity and ennui that had set in on the newsroom since the latter <stro=
ng>Fred Ryan </strong>era, and which Will only exacerbated with his irrever=
ent disregard for traditional <em>Post</em>ian decorum, beyond just the pap=
er=E2=80=99s decision to pull their presidential endorsement. Of course, he=
 was indisputably correct when he told the proud <em>Post </em>newsroom tha=
t no one was reading their stuff=E2=80=94well, it was a slight exaggeration=
=E2=80=94but the affront only made them <em>more</em> dubious about his
ability to lead the paper. At the same time, he didn=E2=80=99t exactly arti=
culate a vision or announce what the <em>Post </em>should be doing <em>diff=
erently</em>, nor how he intended to reverse its nearly $100 million annual=
 revenue losses. Could you blame Carolyn Ryan for preferring to stick aroun=
d at the <em>Times </em>and play the long <strong>Joe Kahn </strong>waiting=
 game?</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">In any event, by the time Egon
Zehnder sent the invoice, it had probably become clear to Will that the bes=
t available option was the guy who had been in the building all along. (Not=
 a great endorsement for Egon Zehnder, alas.) For starters, Matt had alread=
y demonstrated that he could do the job <em>without </em>alienating the sta=
ff. His deference to his boss would also allow Will to effectively serve as=
 the <em>true</em> top editor, a role he held at multiple papers across the=
 pond and seemed keen to replicate when he tried
(and failed) to dissuade Buzbee from pursuing certain stories (a scenario <=
strong>Marty Baron </strong>would never have countenanced). Finally, Will a=
lso knows that Matt will be able to do the tough work of implementing layof=
fs, which will be a necessary part of the grand transformation coming down =
the line=E2=80=94or, frankly, immediately following his coronation.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-=
bottom:0px;">In recent days, Matt has made some internal moves
signaling that he will remain atop the <em>Post</em>, including hiring his =
former <em>Journal </em>managing editor <strong>Karen Pensiero</strong> to =
serve in a newly created position of standards editor.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">If all goes accord=
ing to Lewis=E2=80=99s hopes, Matt may one day find himself with oversight =
of a reinvigorated newsroom. In private conversations, Will has articulated=
 a multifaceted vision for the Post=E2=80=99s future: the core news
report, led by Matt; the opinion section, led by <strong>David Shipley</str=
ong>; the =E2=80=9Cthird newsroom=E2=80=9D WP Ventures arm for new initiati=
ves and verticals, which will be helmed by <strong>Krissah Thompson</strong=
>, reporting in to Matt; and a separate WP Intelligence policy-professional=
 subscription service, led by <strong>Marty Kady</strong>. But getting ther=
e will take a considerable amount of time, since the negativity and ennui a=
re unlikely to abate upon the news that Lewis=E2=80=99s grand plan for the
paper is to promote the guy who is already running the place. Good luck, Ma=
tt. You=E2=80=99re gonna need it.</p></div>
